#Use a Random Forest model to determine the importance of each feature. This gives a clear picture of which features are most influential.
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
importances = RandomForestClassifier().fit(X, Y).feature_importances_
features = X.columns
indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.title("Feature Importance")
plt.bar(range(X.shape[1]), importances[indices], color="b", align="center")
plt.xticks(range(X.shape[1]), [features[i] for i in indices], rotation=90)
plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming these are your models
models = {
    'Logistic Regression': logistic,
    'SVM (RBF Kernel)': rbf,
    'Random Forest': rf,
    'Decision Tree': dt, 
    'KNN': knn,
    'GaussianNB': gauss,
}

# Determine the number of rows and columns for subplots
n_models = len(models)
n_cols = 3  # Number of columns in the subplot grid
n_rows = (n_models + n_cols - 1) // n_cols  # Number of rows needed

# Plot confusion matrices for each model
plt.figure(figsize=(n_cols * 5, n_rows * 5))  # Adjust figure size based on number of subplots
for i, (name, model) in enumerate(models.items(), 1):
    # Generate predictions
    Y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    
    # Compute confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_pred)
    
    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.subplot(n_rows, n_cols, i)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap='Blues', cbar=False)
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix: {name}')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')

plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust subplots to fit into figure area
plt.show()
